Crosstown Traffic (The Jimi Hendrix Experience) played before and as the band walked on stage for the second set. The Altered Beast suite and The Balrog were introduced as new songs. Before Alter Me I, the band took a moment to fix loud buzzing coming from Ambrose's equipment. Invisible Face was incomplete. Am I In Heaven? contained Alter Me and Cellophane teases and quotes, Rattlesnake, Hot Water, and Head On/Pill teases, and a Sea Of Trees jam with lyrics. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. Alter Me I through Am I In Heaven? were confirmed by the band's Facebook livestream. The remaining songs were confirmed through contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. High Voltage (AC/DC) played before and as the band walked on stage for the first set. All Is Known was introduced as a new song and contained alternate lyrics. During Billabong Valley, the guitar strap fell off the Flying Microtonal Banana while Ambrose was using it, with Joey jokingly telling Stu afterwards that his guitar was broken and that Ambrose should "stick to the blues harp". NOBODY'S BABY (Sheer Mag) played before and as the band walked on stage for the second set. Before Gamma Knife, the crowd started chanting for Stu to do a "shoey", to which he told them to "be reasonable" and that he was "too old for that". The Balrog was introduced as a new song. Am I In Heaven? contained a medley of teases and quotes including Alter Me, Cellophane, Rattlesnake, Hot Water, Head On/Pill and The River as well as a Sea of Trees jam with lyrics. This performance was filmed in 360-degree video and released as "King Gizzard & The Lizard Wizard - 360° Full Concert" on the Banalarama YouTube channel, featuring audio mixed by Stu
Sea Of Trees was played for the first time known since 2014-10-24. (217 show gap)

This show featured the debut of Vomit Coffin. Following Rattlesnake, the band wished a happy birthday to Eric. Am I In Heaven? contained teases and quotes of Cellophane, The River, Head On/Pill, I'm In Your Mind, Sea of Trees, Rattlesnake, and Robot Stop. Prior to the show, Stu accidentally posted a link containing demos for all of Polygondwanaland to the Facebook fan page under the name “Blinky Bill”. Although removed shortly after, someone was able to download the first two demos causing Stu to message them claiming he was a fan named Han-Tyumi and asked for the demos not to be reposted. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but no recordings are available. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlist@kglw.net.

This show featured the debuts of Greenhouse Heat Death, D-Day, The Book, Polygondwanaland, and The Fourth Colour. The vocal intro to Nuclear Fusion was not performed. All Is Known was played for the first time since 2018-02-18. (69 show gap) Doom City contained a Crumbling Castle outro. Evil Death Roll was played for the first time since 2017-06-06. (50 show gap) Big Fig Wasp was played for the first time since 2016-09-22. (100 show gap)

The Coffee Cola Song (Francis Bebey) played as the band came on stage. At the start of the show, Joey says this is "the biggest show we've ever played". Before Nuclear Fusion, Joey said that he had said he wasn't going to do the vocal intro anymore, but that he'd "do it tonight". He jokingly apologized to Sam after the vocal intro. The Book was instrumental. Doom City contained a Crumbling Castle outro. Sister Ray (The Velvet Underground) was played over the PA as the setbreak music with a 15 minute countdown on the screen. Han-Tyumi, The Confused Cyborg contained alternate lyrics and Stu on flute. Robot Stop contained a Hot Water tease.

Poster by Olya Dyer limited to 100 prints KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. Big Fig Wasp was confirmed through video recording. The rest of the songs were confirmed via contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

This was the band's first show in Ireland, and took place at the historic Olympia Theatre (later known as 3Olympia Theatre for sponsorship purposes). The band was supported by Mild High Club. Alex Brettin from Mild High Club sat in during King Gizzard's set for D-Day and The Book. God Is In The Rhythm was played for the first time known since 2015-06-24. (241 show gap)

This show featured the debut of Beginner's Luck. Stu sat in on flute with opener Mild High Club on Sketches of Brunswick East II. Alex Brettin from Mild High Club played guitar for D-Day and The Book. Malcolm Brown (formerly of Whitney) played keyboard on Beginner's Luck.

This show featured the debut of Rock N’ Roll. On The Road Again (Rockets) played as the band came on stage. The vocal intro to Nuclear Fusion was not performed. Han-Tyumi, The Confused Cyborg contained alternate lyrics and Stu on flute. Before Rock N’ Roll, Joey had to gently kick a fan off the stage. Stu later mentioned that they were recording the show that night, and that the unreleased song (Rock N’ Roll) was "kinda new". A pro-shot video of The Fourth Colour was released on the Flightless Records YouTube channel. The Fourth Colour contained a tuning session outro with a droning noise playing in the background, and eventually Cellophane teases. Robot Stop contained Master of the Universe (Hawkwind) teases and quotes, and a Hot Water tease. Malcolm Brown (formerly of Whitney) played keyboard on Beginner's Luck. Stu sat in on flute with opener Mild High Club on Sketches of Brunswick East II.
King Khan performed improvised vocals over God Is In The Rhythm

“Electricity” (Captain Beefheart) played from the PA as the band came on stage. Doom City contained a Crumbling Castle outro. Han-Tyumi, The Confused Cyborg featured Stu on flute and alternate lyrics same as the KEXP performance. During the jam before Robot Stop, which contained The River, Am I In Heaven?, and Head On/Pill teases and quotes, Stu shouted out visual artist Jason Galea and wished him a happy birthday. Robot Stop contained a “Master Of The Universe” (Hawkwind) jam with lyrics. Poster by Carlo Vivary
Vomit Coffin was played for the first time since 2017-04-12. (82 show gap) Altered Beast I was played for the first time since 2017-04-18. (78 show gap)

Riff Raff (AC/DC) played as the band came on stage. Before Digital Black, Joey said "this is our biggest show in America, ever", and Stu thanked Amyl & The Sniffers (the opening act). Vomit Coffin was incomplete. Alter Me I was incomplete. Before Rattlesnake, Stu shouted out John Bonham as a "s--t bloke, good drummer", followed by a short Moby Dick (Led Zeppelin) tease. The vocal intro to Nuclear Fusion was not performed. Before The Wheel Joey shouted out Sammy on the sound, Jason Galea who was working the projectors, Gaspard who was working the monitors, and "Nate Dog on the merch". Robot Stop contained Hot Water teases, and the intro contained a Trapdoor tease. Joey thanked Amyl & The Sniffers again after Gamma Knife.

“Whiplash” (Metallica) played as the band came on stage. Vomit Coffin and Alter Me I were incomplete. Before Rattlesnake, Stu shouted out Amyl & The Sniffers, the opening act. Greenhouse Heat Death contained a Sleep Drifter tease. Sleep Drifter contained a Rattlesnake tease. Billabong Valley contained a Sleep Drifter tease. After The Wheel, Joey said "That song was our Jerry Garcia attempt". The intro to Robot Stop contained Trapdoor, Cellophane, and Hot Water teases, and the song itself contained a Hot Water tease. At the end of the show, Joey shouted out the Golden State Warriors, the local NBA team, who were in the midst of the 2018 NBA finals series.

The intro to Robot Stop contained Cellophane and Head On/Pill teases. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but only partial recordings are available. Robot Stop through Big Fig Wasp, Rattlesnake, All Is Known through Digital Black and The Lord of Lightning through Crumbling Castle have been confirmed via audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed by contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.
I'm In Your Mind was played for the first time since 2017-01-21. (133 shows) Alter Me II was played for the first time since 2017-12-02. (50 show gap)

Before Digital Black, Stu asked the crowd if anyone was at the band's previous show in Atlanta, followed by Cavs briefly teasing Moby Dick. Hot Wax, which was played for the first time known since 2016-05-14 (199 show gap), was performed at the request of a fan who asked the band after their previous show if they could play it. Billabong Valley was dedicated to "all them abandoned kitties next door". Sleep Drifter contained a Honey intro tease. After All Is Known, Joey shouted out an audience member's 21st birthday and brought them on stage. Only Part I of The River was played, and it contained a brief blues intro. Wah Wah was played for the first time since 2016-12-09 (138 show gap) and contained The River quotes and teases. Robot Stop contained a “Master Of The Universe” (Hawkwind) jam with lyrics and Hot Water teases.

Planet B and portions of Self-Immolate and Organ Farmer were released on the PHC FILMS YouTube channel. Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before the band as came on stage. Stu and Joey introduced Gaspard, their sound tech, after Murder of the Universe. The band shouted out their sound tech Sammy before Boogieman Sam. Joey thanked openers Stonefield and ORB before Self-Immolate. Evil Star was played through the PA speakers as the band went on stage. Beginner's Luck was introduced as a song about Stu's gambling addiction. After Organ Farmer, Joey thanked openers Stonefield and ORB. Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before and as the band went on stage. Alter Me I contained Evil Death Roll teases. The Bitter Boogie contained Cut Throat Boogie and On The Road Again (Canned Heat) quotes. ‘Inner Cell’, ‘Loyalty’, and ‘Horology’ from this show are featured in the ‘Chunky Shrapnel’ album.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 400

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers before and as the band came on stage. After Billabong Valley a kid was invited on stage to hug the band. Am I In Heaven? contained teases and quotes of Pill, Boogieman Sam, and Alter Me. Organ Farmer was on the setlist before Am I in Heaven? but wasn't played. This show was released through the Official Bootlegger program as Live in Paris ‘19. Poster by Jason Galea Edition of 200

Evil Star was played through the PA speakers as the band went on stage. Cut Throat Boogie contained a Cruel Millennial outro. Wah Wah contained a River intro as well as The River teases and quotes. During the River intro of Wah Wah an audience member got on stage, who Joey then passed his microphone to before security escorted them offstage. Am I In Heaven? contained Robot Stop, Head On/Pill, Cellophane and I'm In Your Mind quotes and teases, Boogieman Sam and Hot Wax quotes and Hot Water teases, as well as featuring Stu on vocoder and later flute for an extended Hot Water jam which was followed by Cavs crowd surfing while Stu played drums. Let Me Mend the Past and Wah Wah from this show are featured in the Chunky Shrapnel album.

Poster By Jason Galea
Edition of 100

This show featured the live debuts of Fury, Some of Us, and O.N.E. Nuclear Fusion did not include the vocal intro, though Joey initially indicated that he was going to have Cavs do it. E. Bobby G. and Leah Senior were shouted out after Static Electricity. Pleura was stopped midway through due to sound issues with the band’s monitors and Joey joked that they were going to make a concept album out of the “fart noises” that only they could hear. The song was then resumed from where they left off. Straws in the Wind was dedicated to Hayden Green. Billabong Valley contained Sleep Drifter and Nuclear Fusion teases. Rattlesnake contained Nuclear Fusion teases. The Reticent Raconteur and The Lord of Lightning featured narration by Leah Senior.

Ambrose was introduced as “The Shrimp Man” before Straws in the Wind. Billabong Valley contained Sleep Drifter and Rattlesnake teases. Sleep Drifter contained Honey and Nuclear Fusion teases. This show was released through the Official Bootlegger program as Live in Melbourne '21.

This show featured the live debuts of See Me and The Hungry Wolf of Fate. Sleep Drifter contained Nuclear Fusion teases. Nuclear Fusion did not include the throat singing intro. Prior to Pleura Stu led a call-and-response chant with the audience, leading Joey to ask “Freddie Mercury who?” Pleura was introduced as a song about Blu-ray. The Hungry Wolf of Fate was printed as “The Hungry Wolf of Fire” on the written setlist. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The available recordings of this show are incomplete (Honey missing; Rattlesnake & Straws in the Wind incomplete). The missing songs were confirmed via the written setlist for this show as well as contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations for the missing or incomplete songs that require audio confirmation (segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

Doom City was stopped & restarted due to equipment issues (bass). As requested by Joey, Cookie provided the vocal intro to Nuclear Fusion. The Book featured a drum solo by Cavs. Straws in the Wind contained Hate Dancin’ quotes. Honey contained Sleep Drifter, Nuclear Fusion and Rattlesnake teases. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The available recordings of this show are incomplete (missing the beginning of Minimum Brain Size). The full setlist was confirmed via the written setlist for this show as well as contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations for missing or incomplete songs that require audio confirmation (segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. This was the Microtonal Night show of the Princess Theatre residency, the third of five planned shows, each featuring a different specific genre and preannounced songs. The Book featured a drum solo by Cavs. Doom City was introduced as a song about planet Earth. Billabong Valley featured guest vocals by Grace Cummings. Rattlesnake contained teases of Sleep Drifter, Honey, O.N.E., Nuclear Fusion and Billabong Valley. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete, but only partial recordings exist. Recordings of K.G.L.W. (Intro) and Automation are unavailable and several other songs are incomplete. The missing songs were confirmed based on the preannounced song lists for each of the 5 planned genre specific shows and contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net. Poster By Jason Galea Edition of 200
Hell was introduced as a song about L.A.  Automation was introduced as a song about the near-term future.

Superbug (lyric changed from “H1N1” to “Coronavirus” referencing COVID-19). Inner Cell was dedicated to the former Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison, who had lost an election that day. Inner Cell was played for the first time since 2019-10-15 (54 show gap), and Loyalty and Horology were played for the first time since 2019-10-18 (52 show gap). Cut Throat Boogie featured Boogieman Sam teases and quotes, Change teases, “Got My Mojo Working” (Ann Cole) quotes, and “My Babe” (Little Walter) quotes. Persistence featured Change teases and Horology teases. Am I in Heaven? featured Cut Throat Boogie, Hot Water, and Change teases and The Dripping Tap, Iron Lung, Cellophane, Persistence, Sea of Trees, Magenta Mountain, and Ice V teases and quotes. The Lord of Lightning was on the printed setlist after Magenta Mountain but was not played.
data.soundcheck: (possibly incomplete) Inner Cell, Loyalty, Magenta Mountain, Mars for the Rich

data.shownotes: Converge (Demo) (or as it was known at the time, Uncolonize) played through the PA as the band walked on stage. Planet B was dedicated to the nearby wildfires. Honey contained Sleep Drifter teases. The Garden Goblin was introduced by Stu as a song Cookie wrote about Lucas, before Cookie clarifies that its about his dog in his garden. There were PA issues during Pleura and the show was paused midway through The Garden Goblin when the PA went down. During the pause the band reminisced about Radiohead's sound cutting out at Coachella 2017, a festival King Gizzard also performed at. Grace Cummings was thanked before Blame It On The Weather. Robot Stop contained Ice V quotes and Hot Water teases. Boogieman Sam contained Cut Throat Boogie quotes and teases. KGLW.net Staff Notes: The setlist for this show is believed to be complete. Gaia through Robot Stop have been confirmed via audio/video recordings. The remaining songs were confirmed via contemporaneous discussions through various social media, but any additional setlist notations that require audio confirmation (guest appearances, segues, quotes or teases) may be incomplete or incorrect. If anyone has any further information or, ideally, a complete or conclusive recording please contact KGLW.net staff at setlists@kglw.net.

This show featured the debut of Ice V. Wah Wah began with the intro to The River, and subsequently contained Crumbling Castle and The River teases. Ambrose quoted It Ain't Me, Babe (Bob Dylan) before Doom City. O.N.E. began with the intro to Straws in the Wind instead of the customary intro. Pleura contained a quote of “Freedom” (Rage Against the Machine). Straws in the Wind was dedicated to Russell Brand. Smoke and Mirrors was played over the PA as the setbreak music. Gaia featured a Cavs drum solo. Ambergris contained an Ice V tease. Before The Reticent Raconteur, Leah Senior was introduced to the stage as “The Original Balrog” and Joey gave a shoutout to her live bass player Jack [Robbins], with the bonus trivia that he was also in Stu’s first band Almacknjack. The Reticent Raconteur was played for the first time since 2021-02-24 (61 show gap). The Reticent Raconteur and The Lord of Lightning featured narration by Leah Senior. The Fourth Colour was played for the first time since 2019-11-23 (70 show gap). Am I in Heaven? contained The Dripping Tap teases. Poster by Jason Galea 800 standard / 50 Foil Print

An I In Heaven? was teased prior to Magenta Mountain. The intro to O.N.E. contained Straws in the Wind teases. The River contained Wah Wah teases and quotes throughout, as well as Crumbling Castle teases. The Land Before Timeland was played over the PA as the setbreak music, which incidentally served as the “debut” for the studio track. Rattlesnake contained teases and quotes from O.N.E., Automation, Honey, and Minimum Brain Size, and teases of Sleep Drifter. Honey contained teases of Sleep Drifter and Billabong Valley. The Reticent Raconteur through The Balrog featured Leah Senior (introduced as “The Balrog” and “the best singer”) providing the narration. Ambrose quoted “Happy Birthday, Lisa” (The Simpsons) while referencing Joey’s “Australian birthday” prior to The Grim Reaper. The Grim Reaper was then introduced as “some weird-ass Satanic rap”. Venusian 2 and Am I in Heaven? were on the printed setlist but were replaced with Planet B due to time constraints. This show was released through the Official Bootlegger program as part of Live at Red Rocks ‘22. Poster By Jason Galea This is the first edition of this print

This show featured the debut of Red Smoke.  Gaia featured a Cavs drum solo over a metal vamp from the band. Leah Senior was shouted out after Hot Water.  Hot Water was reprised during Robot Stop. Work This Time featured a guitar solo.

Poster By Carlo Vivary

Let Me Mend The Past contained an It Ain't Me, Babe (Bob Dylan) quote. Sense was teased immediately before and during Ice V, which contained a Hypertension tease. Ambergris was introduced as “Joey’s porno song”. The Dripping Tap contained Hot Water teases and quotes with the lyrics changed to “time to party” and “everybody wants to party”, and Cellophane teases. Boogieman Sam contained “Going Up the Country” (Canned Heat), “Got My Mojo Working” (Ann Cole), “My Babe” (Little Walter) and “It's a Long Way to the Top (If You Wanna Rock 'N' Roll)” (AC/DC) quotes and Am I In Heaven? teases. Float Along – Fill Your Lungs contained a metal jam. Poster By Lewy Jones

Anoxia was played for the first time since October 18, 2022 (52 show gap). Her and I contained Magenta Mountain and Blindness (The Fall) teases. After the song, Ambrose quotes Walk The Dinosaur (Was (Not Was)). Evil Death Roll contained Witchcraft and Converge teases. Wah Wah contained The River quotes. Only Parts I, II, and III of The River were performer and they contained Her and I (Slow Jam 2), Am I In Heaven?, and Hell's Itch teases. Float Along - Fill Your Lungs contained a Dragon jam. Poster By Jason Galea 420 Standard / 120 Foil

This show featured the debut of Dragon. Am I In Heaven? contained teases of Hot Water and Witchcraft.

Poster By Elora Sperber

Iron Lung contained Hypertension teases.  Hypertension contained Evil Death Roll teases.  Ice V contained Presumptuous and Her and I teases.  Hot Water contained The Dripping Tap quotes and teases.  This Thing contained Hot Water quotes.

Poster By Max Löffler
data.venuename: Plaza Mayor de El Poble Espanyol

data.shownotes: This show featured the debut of Raw Feel. Grace Cummings unfortunately missed a fourth show due to illness, and was replaced with Atlanta, Georgia psych-punk band Upchuck, who Joey thanked at the beginning of the show. Gamma Knife contained an intro jam and Motor Spirit teases. The Dripping Tap, which contained a Head On/Pill tease, had Stu's amp break in the middle, which lead to the song being paused for a short time during which Joey teased “Hey Joe” (Jimi Hendrix) followed by a quote from Ambrose. Nuclear Fusion featured audience member, Earl, on vocals. Honey contained a Sleep Drifter intro that contained Nuclear Fusion teases, and the song itself contained Billabong Valley, Straws In The Wind, and O.N.E teases. Straws In The Wind contained a chant of 'Free Palestine'. Venusian 2 was on the printed setlist after Perihelion but was not played. Poster by Amy Jean; Edition of 150

This show featured the debut of Field of Vision. Daily Blues was preceeded by a Rock and Roll (Led Zeppelin) tease. Gamma Knife contained a Motor Spirit tease. Boogieman Sam contained The Bitter Boogie and Work This Time teases, a Hog Calling Contest vocal jam, and Rats In The Sky quotes. I'm Not In Your Mind contained You Can Be Your Silhouette and Crumbling Castle teases. Cellophane contained Altered Beast teases. Before This Thing, which was introduced as a song about Ambrose and had alternate "New York City" lyrics, Converge was teased. After This Thing, Joey and Stu shouted out "Raygun", the Australian Olypmic breakdancer. Self-Immolate was introduced as a song about God. Straws In The Wind was dedicated to Alex Harvey.  Doom City contained an intro jam. Nuclear Fusion was not on the the printed setlist and featured an audience member (Gabby) on vocals. Rattlesnake contained Honey, Nuclear Fusion, and Oddlife teases, a Field of Vision quote, and Sleep Drifter teases and quotes.

Poster by Jason Galea
Standard Edition of 600
Holographic Edition of 150

The intro to O.N.E. contained a Straws in The Wind tease. The Book was played for the first time since 2023-03-07	(82 show gap). Gaia contained a You Can Be Your Sillhouette tease and featured a drum solo. Plastic Boogie was played for the first time since 2023-06-13 (55 show gap). This Thing contained The Dripping Tap teases and a Hell's Itch tease. Slow Jam 1 and Sense featured Ambrose on sax. Before Field of Vision, the band pretended like they were going to play Hog Calling Contest but they did a jam loosely based on it with lyrics based on the movie The Mask. Big Fig Wasp contained the ending of Robot Stop as the intro. The intro to People-Vultures and the song itself contained Iron Lung jams with lyrics. Iron Lung contained a People-Vultures jam with lyrics.

Poster by Jason Galea
Standard Edition - 600
Foil Edition - 150

Robot Stop featured Ambrose on saxophone and contained Sad Pilot, Converge, and Witchcraft teases. Gamma Knife contained a Motor Spirit tease. People-Vultures contained Iron Lung teases & quotes. Mr. Beat contained Sad Pilot teases. Sad Pilot was introduced as a song about donkeys and dedicated to band soundman Joe Santarpia.  Rats in the Sky was introduced as a song about chickens in the sky. Cut Throat Boogie contained The Bitter Boogie teases and was dedicated to Magic Sam. You Can Be Your Silhouette was dedicated to Alex Brettin of Mild High Club, who then briefly appeared on stage. The Fourth Colour contained quotes of Gila Monster and Mars For the Rich. Straws In the Wind contained a Rattlesnake quote. Welcome to An Altered Future was played for the first time since 2018-03-16. (304 show gap) This was also the first time the suite was performed in full. Set featured Joey on guitar and Ambrose on saxophone. Head On/Pill was not on the written setlist and featured Ambrose on saxophone and contained Am I In Heaven? and Robot Stop teases, Chang'e teases and quotes, and a Hot Water jam with lyrics. At the end of the show, Ambrose thanked Chicago for The Blues Brothers and blues music.

data.shownotes: This show featured the debut of Intrasport, which featured Lucas on Joey's microtonal guitar and Joey on tambourine. Following Billabong Valley Joey shouted out King Stingray and their relationship to Yothu Yindi and Warumpi Band. Hypertension contained teases of Whole Lotta Rosie (AC/DC), La Grange (ZZ Top) and Ice V. Stu teased La Grange again before Antarctica. Joey shouted out Cookie's new Pipe-Eye album in the intro to Ambergris. A segue from Sad Pilot into Rats In the Sky was completed; immediately following the segue the show was stopped for approximately 4 minutes to help a fan who passed out and Rats was then restarted from the beginning. Gaia featured a drum solo by Cavs.

Plastic Boogie contained Hypertension, The Land Before Timeland, The Dripping Tap, and This Thing teases. Straws In The Wind contained I’m Bored (Iggy Pop), Smoke & Mirrors, and Phantom Island quotes. Before Intrasport, the band introduced the synth table with its new nickname "Nathan". Set contained Ice V and Work This Time teases. Extinction contained the Flamethrower quotes from the extended mix. Irong Lung contained Hypertension teases. Hypertension contained a Crumbling Castle tease and a The Dripping Tap tease. Hog Calling Contest was teased before Antarctica, which contained Hot Water teases. Hog Calling Contest and Flight b741 featured Joey on acoustic guitar. The River contained Wah Wah teases and Row, Row, Row Your Boat (traditional) quotes.  Le Risque was on the written setlist after The River but was not played.

Hot Water featured Ambrose on sax. Raw Feel contained a Muddy Water tease and was unfinished. Muddy Water featured Ambrose on sax and contained The Bitter Boogie teases. The Bitter Boogie also featured Ambrose on sax and contained Muddy Water teases as well as an outro jam with lyrics. Gilgamesh contained Magenta Mountain teases and quotes and was unfinished. Before Billabong Valley Ambrose quoted Hits From the Bong (Cypress Hill).  The Great Chain of Being contained The Bitter Boogie teases.

data.shownotes: Slow Jam 1 featured Ambrose on saxophone and contained an Am I In Heaven? tease. Empty was performed for the first time since 2014-12-19 (644 show gap), and was performed with flute for the first time. Hot Wax was played by request of Wayne Gordon (who recorded I'm In Your Mind Fuzz and Quarters! at Daptone Studios and made a brief appearance on stage) and contained an Am I In Heaven? tease. A fan named Callum was brought onto stage to play Superbug on Stu's guitar instead of Stu. Magenta Mountain contained Forty Six & 2 (Tool) and Magma teases. The Grim Reaper contained Forty Six & 2 (Tool) teases and Intergalactic, Sabotage (both Beastie Boys), and Torture Chamber quotes. Following The Grim Reaper, Joey said he was ripping off Wes Borland (of Limp Bizkit), and Ambrose said he needed a red hat (Fred Durst's signature hat). Swan Song contained Magenta Mountain teases and quotes. Le Risque featured Jay Weinberg on drums instead of Cavs. Ice V featured Joey on flute during the intro and contained a quote of Aqualung (Jethro Tull) and teases of Ants & Bats and Blindness (The Fall). Raw Feel contained Am I In Heaven? teases. Hot Water contained I'm In Your Mind and Robot Stop teases.  Following Hot Water, Joey shouted out festival act The Mystery Lights, saying they were the first band they co-headlined with in America. Boogieman Sam contained The Bitter Boogie, Whole Lotta Rosie (AC/DC) and Riff Raff (AC/DC) teases. During Straws In The Wind, Ambrose walked through the crowd to Jason at the soundboard and when he returned to stage, he did an impression of Fred Durst. After Straws In The Wind, the band pretended it was Jason's birthday and sang Happy Birthday to him. During Pleura, Joey said "Fuck Donald Trump", with Ambrose responding "Juicy [Jason] for President!" Dimathaya Burarrwanga and Yimila Gurruwiwi from King Stingray joined the band for Rattlesnake on yiḏaki (didgeridoo), and Dimathaya quoted Treaty (Yothu Yindi). At the end of the show, Joey said Free Palestine and Ambrose led the crowd in a chant of "Free Free Palestine".

Joey said "Fuck Peter Dutton" during the intro of Pleura. Before Magma Joey shouted "Light 'em up, T!" then said that he's always wanted to say that in Australia. Field of Vision contained a quote of Wipeout (The Surfaris).  Dirt was played for the first time since 2024-11-16 (50 show gap) and was played all electric for the first time. During The Dripping Tap, which contained Magma, Machine Gun (Jimi Hendrix) and Cellophane teases, Stu’s amp broke so Joey told a story while another amp was brought out. After Witchcraft, Cavs performed a drum solo while the rest of the band took a break, followed by Cavs taking his own break. The Mind Fuzz suite was introduced as a song by Jimi Hendrix called I'm In Your Mind Fuzz.  I'm Not In Your Mind contained Trapdoor, Machine Gun (Jimi Hendrix) and The Dripping Tap teases.
